Part I - Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Abdellah Ait Ahmed Ouaal¶

Introduction¶

This document is trying to explore about 183413 individual trips made in a bike-sharing system (GoBike) covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.
Our goal is to study the distibution of duration of the trip, and the effect of some predictor factors on the duration essentially the day, the gender and the user type since I expect that those factors will influence the duration of each trip in ways I will try to figure, throughout this investigation, we will try to answer several questions namely:

  • What shape takes the distribution of the duration ?
  • What is the total number of trips per day and hour ?
  • What are hours of the day (24 hours) and days of the week (7 days) with most number of trips ?
  • What relation between duration in one hand and starting days, gender and user type in the other ?

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset had intially 183412 rows and 16 columns, but after we drop missing values the number of rows decreased to 174952, and after we add extracted infos the number of columns rise up to 20 columns, including 2 datetimes, 7 float numbers, one integer (duration in seconds), the rest (10) are all qualitative variables including 4 ordinal variables (start and end of both hour and day).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most intersted in discovering the distribution form of trips duration(in seconds), and figuring out the most occupied trip times or the time with highest number of trips in hours of the day (24 hours) and in days of the week (7 days), as well as the type of the relationship between the duration and the other predictor variables namely starting days, the user type and gender.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the most trips are taken in the early morning hours and in weekends. As for the effect of some predictor variables on the duration, I predict that some factors like gender and user type will reflect different impacts (to discover) on the duration of the trip.

Univariate Exploration¶

The distribution of trip duration in seconds¶

We will start by looking at the distribution of the quantitative variable of interest: duration_sec by using histograms.

In [11]:
# we start with a standard scale plot and we define plot_hist function to reuse it later
def plot_hist(binsize = 100, binstart = tripdata['duration_sec'].min()):
    bins = np.arange(binstart, tripdata['duration_sec'].max() + binsize , binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.hist(data = tripdata, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
    plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds') 
plot_hist();
In [13]:
# we notice that the vast majority of values have a duration less than 3000 seconds, hence we set the first interval [0, 3000]
plot_hist(30)
plt.xlim([0, 3000]);
In [14]:
# then we plot values of the remaining interval [3000, tripdata['duration_sec'].max()] 
plot_hist(binsize = 1000, binstart = 3000)
plt.xlim([3000, tripdata['duration_sec'].max()]);

We notice that there's a long tail in the distribution for the second interval values, which means there is a significant amount of data not shown properly with the normal scale, thus we will use the log scale since it will give us a more clair idea about the distribution of trip durations.

In [15]:
# we use the logarithm scale through xscale and we set appropriate bins and binsize
binsize = 0.03
bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(tripdata['duration_sec'].min()), np.log10(tripdata['duration_sec'].max()) + binsize, binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = tripdata, x = 'duration_sec', bins=bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([50, 1e2, 5e2, 1e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4, 5e4, 1e5], [50, '100', '500', '1000', '5000', '10000', '20000', '50000', '100000'])
plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds');
In [20]:
# we check the mean of the distribution arithmetically
tripdata.duration_sec.mean()
Out[20]:
704.0027436096758

Therefore the trip duration has a lognormal distribution, with the majority of trips have a short duration as they are distributed between 200 and 1000 seconds, with a mean near to 500 seconds (which is actually 704 seconds), and few long trip durations.

The total number of trips per day and hour¶

Now we are going to discover the total number of trips each day of the week in both starting day and ending day, hence we use both ordinal categorical variables start_day and end_day, then we plot them using diagrams.

In [9]:
# we plot our diagrams in days order using countplot order parameter
days = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
def plot_diag(s1, s2 ,size = [10,10], order = days):
    sb.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, figsize = size)
    color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = tripdata, x = s1, order=order, color=color, ax = ax[0])
    sb.countplot(data = tripdata, x = s2, order=order, color=color, ax = ax[1]);
plot_diag('start_day', 'end_day')

As we see the most occupied day in the week is thursday with a total of more than 30000 trips in both start and end day, followed by tuesday, we notice also that the number of trips in all days is greater than 25000 except the weekends since they have the lowest total number of trips taken (under 15000) which is the opposite of what I was expecting!

Next we do the same process to find the total number of trips each hour of the day by calling the two ordinal variables start_hour and end_hour.

In [17]:
# we plot the diagrams in hours order
hours = [str(i) for i in range(24)]
plot_diag('start_hour', 'end_hour', size = [14,10] ,order = hours)

We find that most trips are taken in 17:00 and 18:00 for both starting and ending hour, we notice also that from 10:00 to 15:00 there is an almost stable distrbution of number of trips arround 7500 trips, but from 19:00 to midnight the number of trips decreases drastically, with almost no trips taken in the early morning (before 10:00) which is also the opposite of my expectations.

We could also determine the total number of trips frequency per user type and gender by using the nominal categorical variables user_type and member_gender, user has two possible values: customer or subscriber, and gender has three: male, female and other.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration has a lognormal distribution, we notice first that in normal scale the distribution has a long tail to the right, thus we perform a scale transformation to obtain the log-scale.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, there was two unexpected outcomes: the first is the day when most trips taken was thursday followed by tuesday which was the opposite of my guess(weekends), the second was the hours when most trips are taken (17:00 and 18:00) but I expected they would be the early morning hours.

We drop the missing values and we convert the start_time and end_time to datetime type in order to be able to extract the new variables we've created: start_day, end_day, start_hour and end_hour, because the source variables start_time and end_time have a lot of variables each, which is a break of the rule of tidiness: one variable possess one column.

Bivariate Exploration¶

The effect of the starting day on the duration of the trip¶

We explore the possible effect of the starting day of the week on duration time in seconds, since we study a qualitative vs quantitative variables, we use boxplots.

In [23]:
# we plot our box plots by using boxplot, and not forgetting to chnge the scale of the numerical variable
plt.figure(figsize=[14,7])
sb.boxplot(data=tripdata,x = 'start_day',y='duration_sec',color=sb.color_palette()[0],order=days)
plt.yscale('log')
y_ticklocs=[100,200,500,1e3,2e3,5e3]
y_ticklabels=['100','200','500','1000','2000','5000']
plt.yticks(y_ticklocs,y_ticklabels)
plt.xlabel('Starting Day', labelpad=10)
plt.ylabel('Duration in Seconds')
plt.title('The effect of starting day on the duration of the trip');

We find that long trips are usually taken place in weekends more than the other days of the week, because the third quartile and the median of weekends is slightly above the third quartile of other days.

The effect of the user type on the duration of the trip¶

We do the same as above except this time we are intersted in the possible effect of the user type on duration of the trip.

In [45]:
# we define a function named box_plot to avoid repetition
def plot_box(x='user_type', xlabel='User Type', title='The effect of user type on the duration of the trip'):
    plt.figure(figsize=[6,8])
    sb.boxplot(data=tripdata,x = x,y='duration_sec',color=sb.color_palette()[0])
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.yticks([100,200,500,1e3,2e3,5e3],['100','200','500','1000','2000','5000'])
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, labelpad=10)
    plt.ylabel('Duration in Seconds')
    plt.title('The effect of user type on the duration of the trip');
plot_box()

The above boxplots show us that customers take trips of long duration comparing to subscribers.

The effect of the gender on the duration of the trip¶

Next we see the gender effect on the duration of the trip by using the same function created previously plot_box().

In [35]:
# here we use the predefined function plot_box
plot_box(x='member_gender', xlabel='Gender', title='The effect of gender on the duration of the trip')

As we see from above boxplots, men have shorter trips comparing to othe genders.

The relation between gender and user type¶

We investigate the relation between two qualitative variables: member_gender and user_type, we use clustered bar charts to see if there is a potential relationship.

We discover that there is no obvious relationship between gender and user type.

The relation between starting day and user type¶

Now we move to explore the relationship between starting day and user type.

In [31]:
# we define the function plot_clustered to reuse it later
def plot_clustered (x='user_type', hue='start_day', xlabel='User Type', legend='Starting day', title='Starting day vs User Type', data=tripdata): 
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize']=(14,6)
    sb.countplot(data=data,x=x, hue=hue, hue_order=days)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,labelpad=10)
    plt.legend(title=legend, bbox_to_anchor=(1.2,1))
    plt.title(title);
plot_clustered()
In [34]:
# we take a closer look to customers' users' distribution
filtered_data = tripdata.query('user_type == "Customer"')
plot_clustered (x='user_type', hue='start_day', xlabel='', legend='Starting day', title='Starting day vs Customer', data=filtered_data)

Thursday remains the day (starting day) with most trips for both customers and subscribers, but among customers if we exclude thursday the number of trips each day of the week is between 2000 and 2600 trips(low dispersion), also the second day when most trips are taken is not tuesday, instead it is friday.

We find that long trips occur on weekends more than other days, and customers trips are longer than subscribers trips, also men take shorter trips comparing to other genders.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Among customers the number of trips each day excluding thursday is between 2000 and 2600 trips which means this ditribution has a low dispersion comparing to subscribers distribution, and the second day when most trips are taken is not tuesday instead it is friday. There is no apparent relationship between gender and user type, the same for gender and starting day.

Multivariate Exploration¶

The relation between duration, gender and user type¶

For the multivariate exploration, we explore one case study with two qualitative variables (gender and user type) and one quantitative variable: the duration by using an adapted violinplot.

In [15]:
# we use violin plot in this case
plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])
plt.yscale('log')
sb.violinplot(data=tripdata,x='member_gender',y='duration_sec',hue='user_type',inner='quartile')
plt.yticks([100,200,500,1e3,2e3,5e3],['100','200','500','1000','2000','5000'])
plt.xlabel('Gender', labelpad=15)

We conclude that customers have the longest trip durations in all genders.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We find that in all three genders, the subscribers take shorter trips in duration comparing to customers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

No, as we know the customer especially if it is his first time would usually take longer trip than a subscriber.

Conclusions¶

  • The dataset covers only two months February and March of the year 2019.
  • The numerical variable duration of the trip has a log-normal distribution with a mean of 704 seconds.
  • The day with greatest number of trips is thursday followed by tuesday, and the hour with greatest number of trips is 17:00 followed by 18:00.
  • The subscribers take about 90% of the proportion of users, and men take about 75% of the same proportion.
  • Long trips occur on weekends more than other days.
  • Men take shorter trips comparing to other genders.
  • Customers' trips are longer in duration than subscribers' trips across all genders.
  • Among customers the number of trips each day excluding thursday is between 2000 and 2600 trips, and the second day when most trips are taken is friday.
